I"P<p>Hey everyone! Welcome to Classical Mechanics III. This course is on the topic of <em>Lagrangian and Hamiltonian Mechanics</em>, also known as <em>analytical mechanics</em>. The first half of the course is on Lagrangian Mechanics, and the second on Hamiltonian Mechanics. The first half of the course will contain many real-world examples</p>

<p><a class="page-link" href="/cm-III/introduction">Introduction - What is analytical mechanics? </a></p>

<p><a class="page-link" href="/cm-III/notation">Notation and Conventions </a></p>

<p>The prerequisites are as follows</p>
<ol>
  <li>A strong background in Newtonian mechanics</li>
  <li>A working knowledge of multivariable and vector calculus</li>
  <li>A working knowledge of ordinary differential equations</li>
  <li>A working knowledge of basic electromagnetism</li>
</ol>

